description:
Add Conda source for Python/data science packages.

## Implementation
Conda requires CLI - no simple HTTP API:
```bash
conda search <package> --json 2>/dev/null | jq -r '."<package>"[-1].version'
```

## Challenges:
1. Requires conda installed
2. JSON output is complex (keyed by package name, array of versions)
3. May need to specify channel (defaults, conda-forge)

## Suggested implementation:
```rust
pub struct CondaSource;

impl Source for CondaSource {
    fn name(&self) -> &'static str { "conda" }
    fn ecosystem(&self) -> Ecosystem { Ecosystem::Python }  // Same as pip/uv

    fn get_version(&self, package: &str) -> Option<String> {
        // Check if conda is available
        Command::new("which").arg("conda").output().ok()?.status.success().then_some(())?;

        let output = Command::new("conda")
            .args(["search", package, "--json"])
            .output().ok()?;
        if !output.status.success() { return None; }

        // Parse JSON: {"package_name": [{...version info...}]}
        // Get last entry's version (latest)
        let json = String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stdout);
        // Extract version from last array element
        parse_conda_json(&json, package)
    }
}

fn parse_conda_json(json: &str, package: &str) -> Option<String> {
    // Look for "version":"X.Y.Z" entries, get last one
    json.split(&format!("\"{}\"", package)).nth(1)?
        .rsplit("\"version\":\"").next()?
        .split('"').next()
        .map(|v| v.to_string())
}
```

